<br>
48 Hours bills itself as “investigative journalism.”  Given that moniker I found it ironic that the EQ story contained neither “investigation” nor journalism.  Instead, it was sensationalism devoted on playing on the fears 48 Hour’s Baby Boomer parent demographic.  In this piece of investigative posting, I examine 48 Hours and its abidication of journalistic responsibility.<br>
<br>
The first thing that struck me was the “theme” of 48 hours, namely, addiction.  The show opened with a look at the “sniper” and how he might be addicted to killing.  It seemed to me to be an attempt by 48 hours to quickly try to link the current news of the Sniper to the “addiction” theme so that 48 Hours could get some extra ratings points on the 24/7 Sniper coverage.  <br>
<br>
The problem is that showing the EQ segment right after the Sniper segment, and then trying to link them under the “addiction” theme, unfairly links two things with nothing in common.  The 48 Hours viewer, being justifiably upset at the Sniper story, now watches the EQ segment with the subtle message left by 48 Hours – that EQ is in someway like the Sniper.  That EQ addiction is like the Sniper’s addiction.  It is of no consequence to 48 Hours that there is no objective evidence that the Sniper is addicted to killing, not that EQ is “addictive.”  The attempt to link the two is an intellectually dishonest attempt to play on the fears of its viewers.<br>
<br>
Now, I’ll turn my attempt to the EQ Segment.  The segment opens with a focus on “Jerry” and his family.  Jerry stares blankly at two computer screens, playing two EQ characters at once.  His wife looks on and his two children play, unattended in the background.  As Ms. Stahl asks him questions, he doesn’t even make eye contact with her.<br>
<br>
Jerry’s wife is convinced that he has a problem, and, in truth, he may.  The problem is that by only presenting Jerry, 48 Hours gives viewers the false impression that somehow Jerry is representative of the average player – he is not.  Most are able to keep their play within defined bounds.  I know, personally, we have a rule in my house that I can’t play until my daughter is in bed.  Perhaps the fact that Jerry doesn’t have such a rule is more reflective of he and his wife’s inability to communicate with each other and compromise on child rearing.  <br>
<br>
If 48 Hours really wanted to present a fair story, they would have interviewed other people who can set clearly defined playing boundaries.  That wasn’t their goal though.  They have a story about addiction, a conclusion they reached without investigation and they picked people who would support their “addiction” story, rather than the average person.  That is not “investigation” and it is not “journalism,” it is irresponsible crass sensationalism.  It is also an abdication of a Journalist’s responsibility to the public to fairly cover a story.<br>
<br>
The next segment involved Ben Stein.  Apparently his kid played 24/7 . . . when he was 13!  Mr. Stein, who apparently has a flair for the dramatic, states that it was like an “Evil Spirit” was in his child.  Mr. Stein’s solution was to put his kid in boring school.  Um, ok.<br>
<br>
A couple of things.  First off, it is not exactly recommended to let your 13 year old play an Internet game like EQ in the first place.  If they do though, most parents set clearly defined rules.  Apparently, Mr. Stein did not do this.  He could use his parental authority and limit his child’s play to a coupe of hours a night and on the weekends.  That Mr. Stein’s solution was to send his kid to boarding school shows that he needed someone else to set the boundaries that he failed to do as a parent.  The real story here is not EQ addiction; it is yet one more abdication of parental responsibility.<br>
<br>
Which brings us to the real subject of the 48 Hours piece – the kid who committed suicide.  48 Hours apparently decided to throw away any pretext that it was engaged in objective journalism in this piece.  There were many questions that a good journalist would have asked and investigated.  48 Hours didn’t though, I’ll explain.<br>
<br>
48 Hours begins the story by noting that the boy had “learning disabilities” and “emotional problems.”  Then, amazingly, 48 Hours never addresses these.  48 Hours does not ask which leaning disabilities.  There are many, what does that statement mean?  What “emotional problems” did this person have?  That is a pretty vague category of problems.  Was he angry?  Depressed?  Clinically so?  Was he on medication?  What medication?  I have no idea, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> but a good journalist would have investigated and found out</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.<br>
<br>
The second thing that caught my eye was that he graduated in 1998, and killed himself in 2001.  During that time he had a job for less than a year.  What was his job?  Why did he only have one for less than a year?  Also, they note that he got an apartment.  How did he pay the rent if he did not have a job?  Did his mother pay the rent.  Was he on SSDI and that is how he paid rent?  If he was on SSDI, then it as a real red flag that his emotional problems were serious clinical problems.<br>
<br>
 48 Hours then notes that he quit his job and stopped seeing his family.   His mother speculates that this was due to some “rejection or betrayal” in the game.  What I take from this is that this boy had some real problems dealing with people.  Rejection and betrayal is part of dealing with anyone in life.  Whether he experienced rejection and betrayal in real life, or in EQ, he would experience it at some point in his life – we all do.  However, he had something that made him unable to deal with this.  May I suggest most people would look to his “emotional problems” and not a game?<br>
<br>
Finally, he killed himself on Thanksgiving.  There are always a lot of suicides on Thanksgiving.  People who feel “alone” feel very depressed on such a family holiday.  Perhaps 48 Hours should have mentioned the “Thanksgiving” suicide phenomenon.<br>
<br>
In conclusion, by focusing on a few “extreme” cases and ignoring the vast majority of the 400,000+ player base who do not have problems, by failing to investigate and ask tough questions, and by constructing a sensationalist piece calculated to play on people’s worst fears, 48 Hours ought to be ashamed of itself.  The piece was neither “investigation,” nor was it journalism, and it calls into question the legitimacy of each and every story that 48 Hours covers.  I for one will never watch the show again.  <p>60 Sorcerer | The BoD | The Nameless

