<br>
Most people who are &quot;addicted&quot; to pasttimes such as EQ, golf, etc, simply trade one addition for another as they lose interest in one and gain interest in another.  The object of the addiction is not really all that important to understanding the addictive behaviors (unless there's a pharmacological dependency).  The behaviors will be expressed, and if it's not EQ, then it would be something else.  Ever been to an American Kennel Club event?  Some of the people I've met at AKC shows would cause the hardest of the hardcore EQ players to say &quot;bro, take some time off&quot;.<br>
<br>
So why pick on EQ?  EQ got the attention of dimwits like the CBS producer because it's new, it's got some kind of high-tech angle, Ben Stein is a familiar face to many, and, best of all (from a ratings perspective), there are bloodstains to be show on TV.  (For those of you who didn't see it, yes, they showed photos of the periphery of the suicide scene.  Two or three times, just in case you missed the first one.)  Put all these elements together and you've got a good fit in some audience profiler's formula for good ratings.  Also, it probably doesn't hurt that EQ's corporate parent (Sony) is a competitor in the media industry where CBS lives.<br>
<br>
It's just television, try not to take it too seriously.<br>
